ivity and environmental context without changing the literature mechanism (Yamabe et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanide addition to the imine manifold forming alanine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_005\",\n        \"mol_003\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_006\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"montmorillonite\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"aqueous modeling study; not reported numerically\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none reported in source study; mineral surfaces included as concentrators\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous Strecker setting; proton-transfer dependent; racemic aminonitrile expected absent chiral bias\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic cyanide addition to the imine/carbinolamine manifold yields 2-aminopropanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The validated report identifies this as the second mechanistically explicit Strecker step leading directly to alanine aminonitrile, with stereochemistry expected to be racemic without a chiral bias. Mineral catalysis was not reported in the preserved source, so the added surface agents are explicitly contextual rather than literature-asserted catalysts (Yamabe et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of alanine aminonitrile to alanine amide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_006\",\n        \"mol_004\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_007\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\",\n        \"montmorillonite\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"hydrolytic aqueous regime; numeric value not recovered\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported\",\n        \"catalyst