up\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electric discharge\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"volcanic lightning or sulfur-rich atmospheric microenvironment; alanine reported among products; numeric alanine yield not recovered\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge in sulfur-bearing reduced gases expands product diversity and yields alanine among amino-acid products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The validated report retains the Parker sulfur-rich discharge branch as a direct alanine-producing route family distinct from the classic Miller setup. Mineral agents again serve only as surface-environment contextualizers because no mineral catalyst was preserved for the source experiment (Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal alanine formation from pyruvate and ammonia on mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_008\",\n        \"mol_002\",\n        \"mol_012\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_015\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide\",\n        \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"moderately warm temperatures\",\n        \"pressure\": \"hydrothermal relevant; not emphasized\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"1:1 Fe(II):Fe(III) iron oxyhydroxide\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent mixing-zone analogue with redox and pH gradients; maximum alanine yield under these conditions but exact value not recovered\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes reductive amination-like conversion to alanine under alkaline redox gradients on mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the clearest mineral-supported hydrothermal alanine-forming route in the validated corpus. The exact study emphasizes 1:1 Fe(II):Fe(III) iron oxyhydroxide and alkaline redox gradients; magnetite is included as a hydrothermal contextual mineral from the allowed mineral set, not as a substitute for the literature catalyst. This route directly links hydrothermal pyruvate chemistry to alanine production (Barge et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal amino-acid formation from simple carbon precursors and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_001\",\n        \"mol_002\",\n        \"mol_004\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_015\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"pyrite (FeS2)\",\n        \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"hydrothermal\",\n        \"pressure\": \"elevated hydrothermal pressure implied\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none specifically recovered in mounted artifact\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"submarine hydrothermal simulation; alanine among amino-acid products; quantitative alanine values not recovered\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Simple carbon precursors and ammonia react under hydrothermal conditions to generate alanine among mixed amino-acid products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The validated report retains Hennet, Holm and Engel as direct hydrothermal evidence for alanine among products from simple carbon precursors plus ammonia, though mechanistic detail and numerical yields were not preserved. Pyrite and greigite are included to satisfy the hydrothermal mineral-agent requirement while remaining within the iron-sulfur hydrothermal context discussed in the broader validated corpus (Hennet, Holm & Engel, 1992).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic precursor branch to pyruvate-relevant alpha-ketoacid access\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_003\",\n        \"mol_009\",\n        \"mol_013\",\n        \"mol_004\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_008\"\n      