nce >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: L-Alanine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network follows the literature-supported prebiotic route families retained in the validated report for alanine: (i) the mechanistically explicit Strecker sequence from acetaldehyde, ammonia, and HCN via imine/carbinolamine, alanine aminonitrile, and alanine amide; (ii) direct atmospheric spark-discharge formation of alanine from reduced gas mixtures, including sulfur-rich variants; (iii) hydrothermal pyruvate amination under alkaline redox gradients on mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide; (iv) hydrothermal amino-acid formation from simple carbon precursors plus ammonia; (v) astrochemical UV/VUV ice photochemistry yielding racemic alanine; (vi) CPL-associated UV ice processing giving only weak enantiomeric excess; and (vii) cyanosulfidic and iron-sulfur branches that are retained as precursor-generating or inferred alanine-forming routes. Because the evidence base supports mostly racemic or unspecified alanine rather than enantiopure L-alanine, the final L-alanine node is treated as arising from weakly biased selection/resolution from prebiotically formed alanine in biochemical settings, explicitly acknowledging this as the major unresolved gap in the literature. Ten distinct pathways are enumerated by combining the direct route families and literature-consistent sub-branches to the common alanine hub, followed by a final biochemical enantioenrichment/selection step.\n\nMOLECULES (17 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CH3CHO (acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_002: NH3 (ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_003: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_005: C2H5NO (acetaldehyde-ammonia imine/carbinolamine manifold) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: C3H6N2 (alanine aminonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C3H7NO (alanine amide) [intermedia