anch is appropriately included because it appears in the validated literature set, but the report explicitly characterizes it as inferred, contested, and weakly supported by direct alanine evidence. It is therefore one of the least secure pathways in the network.', 'The astrochemical UV/VUV and CPL-associated routes are well aligned with the literature for racemic alanine and weak enantiomeric excess formation in ice residues. The major limitation is environmental translation to early Earth surface chemistry and the very small ee values, which do not justify a direct route to L-alanine.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.72\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong and substantially literature-aware. It includes sufficient molecule and reaction nodes, identifies reasonable hub molecules, and captures multiple convergent branches to alanine. The strongest parts are the Strecker sequence, spark-discharge production, Barge-style hydrothermal pyruvate amination, and astrochemical alanine formation, all of which are consistent with the supplied research. It also correctly treats cyanosulfidic and iron-sulfur branches as weaker or inferred. Major weaknesses prevent approval. First, the target is L-alanine, but the literature supports mostly racemic or unspecified alanine; rxn_014 is explicitly speculative and materially lowers target achievement. Second, some pathway-completion reactions are chemically oversimplified relative to the literature, especially rxn_009 and rxn_010. Third, environmental labeling is not always precise: spark discharge is atmospheric rather than simply surface, and astrochemical ice chemistry is cryogenic/extraterrestrial rather than a standard surface pool setting. Fourth, while the user summary does not list mineral agents for every hydrothermal and surface reaction, the evaluation is limited by the provided abstracted network representation rather than full JSON fields. Overall, this is a good alanine network but not an approved L-alanine 