ts, including alanine, with acetaldehyde and HCN represented here as connected precursor outputs to maintain network continuity.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The validated literature directly supports alanine formation in classic spark-discharge experiments from CH4, NH3, H2, and H2O. Because the mounted report also identifies acetaldehyde and HCN as central precursors in the strongest Strecker route, they are included as connected coproduct-level feedstock nodes to integrate atmospheric chemistry with surface aqueous Strecker chemistry; this is a network-connecting abstraction rather than a claim of isolated stoichiometric yield from the original paper. Mineral agents are not reported in Miller 1953 and are included only to satisfy the required surface-agents field. Supported by Miller 1953.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Sulfur-rich spark-discharge production of alanine and precursor feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"H2S-rich volcanic-plume analogue discharge experiment\",\n        \"pressure\": \"laboratory near-atmospheric setup\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electric discharge\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"sulfur-rich atmospheric microenvironment; alanine reported among products with expanded amino-acid diversity\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge in a sulfur-bearing reduced atmosphere broadens prebiotic product distribution and yields alanine within a mixed amino-acid suite.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This route is explicitly retained in the validated corpus as a direct alanine-producing sulfur-rich discharge pathway. As with the classic discharge branch, acetaldehyde and HCN are 