ssure\": \"low-pressure astrochemical simulation\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-CPL photons\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"small enantiomeric excess only; maximum ee in ice-alone scenarios on the order of ~1%\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CPL-driven asymmetric photochemistry in ice analogues yields alanine after hydrolysis with only very small enantiomeric bias.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The validated corpus preserves only weak asymmetry evidence, with alanine formed after CPL irradiation but with at most very small ee values around ~1%. Both alanine and L-alanine are output here to reflect that the dominant product remains essentially alanine/racemate while a minor L-enriched fraction is possible. This should not be interpreted as a demonstrated route to enantiopure L-alanine. Mineral agents are schema-required only. Supported by de Marcellus et al. 2007; Sharma 2022; 2015 OLEB alanine CPL study.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic assembly of alanine into oligopeptides\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"hydrothermal microflow / warm to hot aqueous conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"flow-reactor / hydrothermal\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"various minerals can enhance or inhibit elongation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"downstream assembly edge once alanine is available\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alanine monomers undergo condensation/oligomerization under hydrothermal-flow or mineral-influenced conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is included because the validated corpus explicitly preserves alanine-to-oligopeptide assembly as downstream chemistry relevant to prebiotic progression once alanine is present. It is not a route to alanine itself. Supported by Kawamura et al. 2005; Kawamura et al. 2018.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative prebiotic enrichment/selection from alanine to L-alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to localized compartmental\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none established\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"geochemical or physical selection/enrichment step not directly validated in mounted literature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Weak asymmetric enrichment or selective retention of one enantiomer from a predominantly racemic alanine pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is explicitly speculative and included only because the requested target is L-alanine while the validated literature overwhelmingly supports racemic or unspecified alanine and no robust route to enantiopure L-alanine. The only preserved asymmetry evidence is very small CPL-associated ee, far from a demonstrated L-alanine synthesis pathway. This reaction therefore represents an unresolved gap rather than a validated synthesis. Grounded by the gap analysis in de Marcellus et al. 2007; Sharma 2022; 2015 OLEB alanine CPL study, and the executive conclusion of the supplied report.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical Strecker route to alanine then speculative L-selection\",\n      \"description\": \"Best-supported mechanistic pathway: acetaldehyde forms an imine/carbinolamine manifold with ammonia and water, cyanide addition gives alanine aminonitrile, and hydrolysis via alanine amide yields alanine; L-alanine remains unresolved and requires a speculative enrichment step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_