rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "H2S-rich volcanic-plume analogue discharge experiment", "pressure": "laboratory near-atmospheric setup", "catalyst": "electric discharge", "aqueous": "true", "other": "sulfur-rich atmospheric microenvironment; alanine reported among products with expanded amino-acid diversity"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge in a sulfur-bearing reduced atmosphere broadens prebiotic product distribution and yields alanine within a mixed amino-acid suite.", "reasoning": "This route is explicitly retained in the validated corpus as a direct alanine-producing sulfur-rich discharge pathway. As with the classic discharge branch, acetaldehyde and HCN are included as connected network feedstocks to show atmospheric-to-surface precursor flow rather than to imply exact isolated stoichiometry from the source experiment. Mineral agents are schema-required placeholders and not literature-established catalysts for the discharge itself. Supported by Parker et al. 2011."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_002", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide (1:1 Fe(II):Fe(III))", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "moderately warm temperatures", "pressure": "hydrothermal relevant; not emphasized", "catalyst": "1:1 Fe(II):Fe(III) iron oxyhydroxide", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent mixing-zone analogue with redox and pH gradients; exact alanine yield not recovered in mounted artifact"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes mineral-assisted amination/reductive amination-like conversion to alanine under alkaline redox gradients.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest mineral-coupled hydrothermal alanine-forming route in the validated report. Conditions, alkaline setting, and 1:1 Fe(II):Fe(III) iron oxyhy